Mobiles.LongDescription: Red, the trusted bailiff, stands here stoically.
Mobiles.Description: Red follows the orders of the judge...without fail. It's best to do whathe asks, and don't ask alot of questions. He's not here to give you answers.And giving him any trouble could be your downfall.

Mobiles.LongDescription: A small food vendor is here to wait on you.
Mobiles.Description: The small man bakes up some of the most delectible meat pies in the realm,and they are so warm and filling. Just don't be too inquisitive about theingredients. You might loose your desire to eat...Bon Appetite!

Mobiles.LongDescription: The keeper of the gaol gate stands here.
Mobiles.Description: The gatekeeper doesn't seem to be a mean fellow, but it is doubtful that hewould take any guff from people coming to the gaol. He isn't exactly polite,and he wasn't given this job to be that way...

Mobiles.LongDescription: The warden of the gaol looks at you menacingly!
Mobiles.Description: The warden looks to be in fantastic shape for spending his days down in thishole. He has seen many battles and riots, and fears no one. He has many scarsto show for his battles to the death, and yet he is still here.

Mobiles.LongDescription: A guard stands watch over the gaol.
Mobiles.Description: The lift guard is here to watch over the prisoners and to keep outsiders fromentering the prison for any unlawful reasons. They tend to dislike thisassignment, but it's all part of the job. They do take great pride in keepingany prisoners from escaping...

Mobiles.LongDescription: There is a hulking man here watching the prisoners labor.
Mobiles.Description: The liftmaster is a huge man dressed in studded leather. He is a completeand total slavemaster without compassion. If you end up battling with him,don't expect mercy...you won't get it.

Mobiles.LongDescription: A gaol guard is taking a well-deserved break here.
Mobiles.Description: This big fellow certainly dislikes being roused from sleep to deal withproblems in the gaol. Ever hear of the old adage involving sleeping dogs?

Mobiles.LongDescription: There is a worn and bedragled prisoner eyeing you.
Mobiles.Description: You can only wonder what crime this poor wretch commited to be sentanced tothis foul place. It seems as if he has been here for quite some time. You canonly hope that your stay here will not be as long...

Mobiles.LongDescription: There is a scrawny prisoner here who is being forced to move the wheel.
Mobiles.Description: The prisoner begs for your help...you MUST be here on a rescue mission.He thinks he can help you! you might ask him the secrets of the gaol...

Mobiles.LongDescription: Gregg, the community guildmaster is here.
Mobiles.Description: Greggory is trained in all professions but is a master of none of them.He will be able to help you gain some levels, but for practicing yourskills, you're better off heading to thesden.  Once a youth of manyaspirations, time has worn this man down.  He wears shabby clothes and ismissing some teeth.  Since he never really completed a specific profession,he wound up poor, living under this bridge.  Poor Greggory.

Mobiles.LongDescription: The professor of the General Law of Exodus sits at her desk.
Mobiles.Description: The law professor is well versed in the court system and proceedures. You canlearn quite a bit from this individual if you take the time to ask the properquestions. As in most cases, the quality of your education depends on you...

Mobiles.LongDescription: The professor of Courtroom Procedure stands at the blackboard
Mobiles.Description: The law professor is well versed in the court system and procedures.  Youcan learn quite a bit from this individual if you take the time to ask theproper questions.  As in most cases, the quality of your education dependson you...

Mobiles.LongDescription: The professor teaching the Pre-trial Motion class stands before you.
Mobiles.Description: The law professor is well versed in the court system and proceedures. You canlearn quite a bit from this individual if you take the time to ask the properquestions. As in most cases, the quality of your education depends on you...

Mobiles.LongDescription: The instructor of Jury Selection proceedure sits at his desk.
Mobiles.Description: The law professor is well versed in the court system and proceedures. You canlearn quite a bit from this individual if you take the time to ask the properquestions. As in most cases, the quality of your education depends on you...

Mobiles.LongDescription: The Common Objections class professor waits patiently at his desk.
Mobiles.Description: The law professor is well versed in the court system and proceedures. You canlearn quite a bit from this individual if you take the time to ask the properquestions. As in most cases, the quality of your education depends on you...

Mobiles.LongDescription: The professor of the Barrister Ethics class waits to give instruction.
Mobiles.Description: The law professor is well versed in the court system and proceedures. You canlearn quite a bit from this individual if you take the time to ask the properquestions. As in most cases, the quality of your education depends on you...

Mobiles.LongDescription: The Registrar waits behind a counter to enroll you in the Law School.
Mobiles.Description: The registrar is a older woman who regards the new students pensively. Sherealizes that the fate of some will rest in the hands of those who pass thesedoors. She also wonders if you have ever been in trouble with the law...

Mobiles.ShortDescription: The Dean of Exodus Law School
Mobiles.LongDescription: The Dean of Exodus Law School welcomes you.
Mobiles.Description: The Dean is here to discuss the future of prospective students. She is a kindwoman who has all the credentials to handle the job. She is easy to talk with,and even easier to like.
Shaft the pimp is one heck of a dude...`hShaft the pimp is in excellent condition.Shaft the pimp is using:<worn on penis>    `dA monstrous cock ring

Rooms.TpMsg: Judge Malakai grants you 500 experience points for discovering the courtroom.
Rooms.RoomDescription: `oThe courtroom is a majestic place created in the finest traditions. Thepanelling is solid mahogany as are the furnishings in the room. The ceilingsare of great height. Two Giants standing upon one another would not reachits limit. There is a tall bench for the judge who will rule over all ofthe proceedings here. And Beyond, the flags which represent all of therealms of Exodus are flown. In the center of the colors, a gold seal whichreads "Regnat Populus". To the right of the bench, there is a half wall,which separates the jury from the remainder of the room. The rear of thechamber has the seating area for the spectators who are sure to come...

The jury room is rather stark compared to the majesty of the main courtroom.Although the materials of construction remain the same, there are no bannersor flags here. There is a large board for the jurors to write upon, and somefurnishings which include a large table and chairs. But it is obvious thatthis room isn't built for comfort...it is here for work.

The corridor leading to and from the courtroom is lavish indeed. It seemsit was created for the elite of the legal profession. While the entirebuilding is made of fine materials, this area has added amenities such assolid brass hardware and exotic dark marble flooring. The floor is polishedto a sheen that relects the ensconced lighting that lines the hall. Justsouth is a panel that leads to the courtroom proper, and there are severaldoors to the north.

This is about the middle of the corridor. A couple of steps to the northor south, you see a large door and a sliding panel, respectively. Directlywest there is a large conference room. To the east, there is a room packedfull of books and such. This portion of the courts is usually open only tobarristers and members of the court. Be aware of this.

The corridor extends to the south, and to the north is a large wooden door.It is, of course, constructed of mahogany, and has a brass plate mounted ateye level. The hall is also panelled with the fine wood, and is in finecombination with the dark surface of the polished marble floor. The floorreflects the low lighting of the hallway which eminates from shell shapedsconces mounted on the walls.

At the end of this long marble hallway, there are two huge mahogany doorswhich lead into the Crimson Court of Exodus. If you are coming to watch atrial, you may enter and be seated. Be aware that the courtroom is a seriousplace, and disrespect will not be tolerated. If you have been subpeoned bythe courts, you must wait here to be called in by the baliff. Make yourselfcomfortable, and you may make use of the snack room to the east.

`hThis small room is dedicated to the men and women who are council for thedefense. These are the only persons allowed here, and unless you legallyposess an Exodus Bar Exam diploma, you'd best be leaving. The hallway isto the east, and to the north, is the holding cell where the barristers maymeet with their clients. Make `bSURE`` that the hall door is `bCLOSED`` and `bLOCKED``,before entering the cell, and lock the cell door behind you. Barristers areresponsible for clients being held for trial.

The snack room is a small alcove where you may purchase inexpensive foodswhile waiting on the trial. The floors and walls are finished in marble andmahogany, as are most of the rooms on this floor. It may seem a bit muchjust for a little vending stand, but it fits... You best not tarry here forlong if you are waiting to be called as a witness.

The middle of the windowless corridor echos with every footstep. The darkmarble flooring picks up every click of the heels and throws it off thefinely crafted mahogany woodwork. There is a large set of double doors tothe north with seating benches on its flanks. To the south, there is a largemetal gate which closes of the lift shaft to prevent falls. The sconces onthe walls shed quite a bit of light and makes the hallway bright.

The top floor of the Courts Building is the most elegant of all. The floorsare of the finest dark marble, the woodwork in mahogany, and the lightingfixtures are of crystal. There was no expense spared in the construction ofthe structure. Discussion in the place is most often done in hushed toneseven though the soft voices still carry quite far. Off to the north, thereis a large set of doors, and directly to the south is a metal cage whichleads to a lift for travel between floors.

This room, even in splendor, is built for business. The large area isfilled in part by a large table that will seat quite a few people. Thenorth and west walls light the space generously during the day, and afforda spectacular view of the city lights at night. But most often, theoccupants of the place have other things to discuss.

The library has the musty smell that is often associated with old legal booksand papers. The leather bound volumes are well oiled by use, however, and soare the tall back leather chairs meant for the readers. The wise and prudentbarrister studies the case history and precedent set forth here. There arealso several publications on the legal proceedure for the Court of Exodus.Being farmiliar with the workings of the court will certainly win points withthe bench...The books here are not to leave the room.

The old cage looks as if may plummet to the bottom of the building at anyminute.  But, surprisingly, it holds all the weight that is piled into it.The motion of the lift is very erratic, and one may wonder what gives itpower...

The main lobby is the crossroads of the Courts Building. People of all racesand sizes pass one another to attend to business in the building. The commonfactor they all have is that the business is most likely legal in nature,although it varies from there. The decor of the building is certainly stunningin its materials and workmanship. There is a set of mesh doors directly tothe south which protect the public from the lift shaft. The main lobbycontinues to the north.

The first impression of the prison is the assault of the putrid air uponthe olfactory nerves. The light from the shaft which houses the lift radiatesinto a small circle, but beyond that it is difficult to see. As eyes areadjusting to the dim light, the small sounds of the old gaol are heard. Thefaint dripping of water adds to the clammy feel of the air, and low soundsfrom small animals are present. Then the eyes begin to focus, and the waynorth can be seen, but the small room in that direction is blocked by thickmetal bars. Without a key, it is impassable...

The lobby of the Courts Building is stunning in its elegance. Hanging froma barrel vaulted ceiling, which runs the length of the lobby, is a candlelitchandelier. It sheds light on the dark mahogany panelling and woodwork of thewalls and trim, and reflects from the polished marble floors. This rich decoris carried out through most of the building that is visited by the generalpublic. There are a few furnishings about the room, some seating areas thatare decorated with indoor plants imported from more tropical lands, and nooksthat provide a private place to discuss the business of the courts. The lobbyruns north and south with the length of the structure.

This room is a bit larger than the gated checkpoint which houses guards tothe south. To the east and west, there are unmarked doors created from largetimbers and strapped with iron. A smaller corridor runs north, and along it,there are many doors which appear to be made entirely of metal. The hallwayis much darker, and it is difficult to see the entire length from this placewhich is lighted by several wall mounted torches.

Rooms.MaxMsg: There's too many people in there already!
Rooms.RoomDescription: A small gust of fresh air from above momentarily blows away the putrid smellof the prison. The stovepipe from a small cookstove leads upward into a smallhole where the outside air finds its way into the room. The cookstove takesthe chill off of the people who spend time in this room, and even provide thecreature comforts of a warm meal or drink. Being one of the prison guards hasvery few benefiets, but it is much better than residing here as one of theprisoners... This area has barred gates to the north and south, and the wallsare chisled from solid bedrock. Escaping from this place is next to impossiblewithout some kind of assistance.

The passage is poorly lit by torches which are hanging upon the walls. Theflickering illumination gives brief glimpses into the dank cells which areclosed and locked on both sides of the corridor. From off in the distance,there is the sound of dripping water, but it doesn't seem possible to placethe exact location. Aside from barely audibly moans that occasionallyeminate from one of the cells, and the squeek of the rodents, the place isquiet. But it's the unnerving type of quiet that places butterflies in thepit of your stomach...

Rooms.MaxMsg: That room isn't big enough for another person!
Rooms.RoomDescription: The passage off of the antechamber is a bit tight. It is also darker than theother rooms of the gaol, making it impossible to see the way south. You canfeel that the tunnel not only narrows, but slopes downward in that direstion.The walls are hewn from the bedrock, but they aren't sharp. It's as if theyhave been worn down over time, but it's a wonder what wore them down. Thedoor back to the antechamber is a thick and solid wooden door with a smallbarred rectangle at eye level. One might ponder as to its unlocked state...

Rooms.MaxMsg: You can only move in single file down this tunnel.
Rooms.RoomDescription: The small throat of the tunnelway is barely wide enough to allow a large manto pass without turning to the side. The small size of the space, along withthe lack of light, would make fighting difficult. The slope of the floor maygive some advantage if you meet a foe face to face, but it would be best notto have one come at you from the north. It looks as if the adit widens bothto the north and south, and not a moment too soon...

Rooms.MaxMsg: The tunnel is too small for you to fit...
Rooms.RoomDescription: The passage turns to the west and opens into a larger cavern. Althoughis darker in the larger space, flashes of light illuminate what appears tobe a large spoked wheel. The occasional light comes from a small board onthe wheel. The machinery, it turns out, powers the lift that is used totravel between the floors of the building. The force used to turn the wheeldefies decency...it is moved by the pitiful men being held in this horridplace!

Rooms.MaxMsg: The wheel pit is too crowded for you to jump down...
Rooms.RoomDescription: The circular pit of the lift mill is several feet below the grade of theother parts of this level. The arms of the wheel, to which the prisoners arechained, are about six feet long. Just long enough to give the men enoughleverage to move the large machine. The entire pit might be fifteen or sixteenfeet in diameter, with just enough space for a sizable person to stand, backagainst the wall, and stay clear of the wheel arms as they move. The noisygrinding of the gears and mechanisms slows to a stop as you enter...

Rooms.MaxMsg: The tunnel is too small for you to fit...
Rooms.RoomDescription: The passage turns to the west and opens into a larger cavern. Although itis darker in the larger space, flashes of light illuminate what appears tobe a large spoked wheel. The occasional light comes from a small board onthe wheel. The machinery, it turns out, powers the lift that is used totravel between the floors of the building. The force used to turn the wheeldefies decency...it is moved by the pitiful men being held in this horridplace!

Rooms.MaxMsg: You can only move in single file down the tunnel.
Rooms.RoomDescription: The tunnelway is barely passable for two men. In fact, two men passing oneanother is this tight place is almost impossible. The problem that visitorsface, however, is that none of the men that habit the dank underground arewilling to allow others to pass. Any visitors to this prison may end up aspermanant residents if they cannot fight their way out. And feeling therough stone walls of the tunnel, one might realize that overwhelming theseguards is the only way out...

Rooms.MaxMsg: That little room can only hold two people...
Rooms.RoomDescription: The small room carved out of the earth leads south into a tunnelway thatslopes downward. The west entry to the room has a large wooden door that looksas if it has been carved from a solid slad of wood. The door has a barredrectangle from which a person could look out into the antechamber. The lightis dim in the gaol to begin with, but this area seems to be completely withouttorches to illuminate the way. Moving south through the tunnel will requirea light to be held in front of the body, making things very difficult.

Quiet footsteps and whispers seem to echo through the halls as stomping andshouting. It is difficult to keep from running or hiding, but it is imperativethat one keeps a cool head. The fewer people that know your whereabouts thebetter. The flickering of the torches flashes shadows that pull hushed gaspsfrom the lungs and make the hair rise on the back of the neck. The reasonfor intruding into the prison had best be worth the effort...

Towards the middle of the corridor, it becomes quite difficult to discernone end of the hall from the other. It would be best if a visitor in thispart of the gaol did not lose their way. Getting directions mixed up couldcertainly end in tragedy. The unnerving quiet is relentless, and what fewsounds occur seem to fade and strengthen in volume. It is hard to imaginethat any of the prison guards could be close by...

At the far northern end of the hallway, there is another large wood slab doorwith a rectangular viewing portal. Although it is of solid construction, it isnot of the same unbreakable materials as the cell doors. It is also unlocked,which might lead a person to believe that it isn't one of the safest placesin the prison. Sneaking up to the portal, you can hear movement and soundscoming from the other side. It seems to be occupied. There is also a slightbreeze blowing fresh air from the slot in the door.  It is quite a relief fromthe fetid air that hangs thickly over the prison.

The private room of the presiding Judge is surprisingly sparse for theamount of time that must be spent here. There is a large desk which iscovered with a clutter of papers, and a comfortable looking chair. Thewalls about the room are mostly fronted by bookshelves which rise almostto the height of the ceiling. There are a few knick-knacks that top thecases. There is also a couch and a few chairs scattered about the roomfor the persons who are brought to the chamber for discussion. You mightwant to wait for an invitation to be seated...

What a wretched place! The poor souls kept in this dungeon are not giventhe treatment one would give an animal. Foul water from above drips down theslime covered walls onto a floor which is constantly wet. And on the floor,there is a rodent gnawed and lice infested mat made from straw. There areunreadable scrawls scratched into the water softened face of the large stoneswhich comprise the walls separating the adjoining cells. If those walls couldspeak...

Rooms.MaxMsg: That room is too full for you to slip in...
Rooms.RoomDescription: Oh My! This is the room where the guards who are not on duty come to sleep!The good news is that more often than not, when the guards are here in theroom, they're asleep! The noise heard from outside the door was snoring andrestless sleep. The first instinct is to just slip back out of here, but thewonderful fresh air coming from a shaft in the ceiling fills your lungs.After being down here for a few minutes, one can almost forget how pleasantthe outdoor air can be! Then you notice the size of the covered shapes thatlie on the metal bunks lining the walls...

The main lobby is the crossroads of the Courts Building. People of all racesand sizes pass one another to attend to business in the building. The commonfactor they all have is that the business is most likely legal in nature,although it varies from there. The decor of the building is certainly stunningin its materials and workmanship. To the north, a set of glass paned doorsleads to the hall of Barristers, which houses law firms of the realm. Themain lobby continues on to the south.

The twin sets of double doors all stand wide open to the public. It seemsthat this building is open to all comers, but it may not be so easy for thepersons who wish to leave...at least the ones who have committed a crime.The surrounding in the building are much more regal in their style than theother buildings in this part of town. It seems that the designers of thisstructure spared little expense in the construction. Off to the west isOld Cobble Road, and the main lobby of the Courts Building is east.

The twin sets of double doors all stand wide open to the public. It seemsthat this building is open to all comers, but it may not be so easy for thepersons who wish to leave...at least the ones who have committed a crime.The surrounding in the building are much more regal in their style than theother buildings in this part of town. It seems that the designers of thisstructure spared little expense in the construction. An old cobbled pathleads south to Gallows Square, and west is the main lobby.

The main floor of the Courts Building is dedicated to the people who havecompleted the rigorous education and testing that is required to practice lawin the realms of Exodus. They are the only persons who are allowed to buildoffices along this hall. If a player finds themselves in trouble with thelaw, this is the place to come. There are office doors on either side of thehallway which house the various barristers, and signs hang from the ceilingwith the names of their firms.

The corridor leading from the south widens into a room which houses the officeof the registrar of the school. There are some nice wall hangings and plantsbrighten the windowless room. There are a few pieces of tasteful furniturescattered about for waiting students. It seems as if the registrar also actsas secretary to the Dean of the school. This school is very small, but it isalso the most highly regarded.

The Law School has a fine reception area for meeting guests and alumni, butit is also where the Dean of the school confers with the students who areentering the school. He tries to prepare them for the ardous journey on whichthey are about to embark. The room is comfortable with soft lighting, and itis a place for the students to feel at home...because it will seem that wayuntil graduation. It is not uncommon to find one of the law students asleepon the couch in the middle of the night.

The halls of the school are elegant without the smallest hint of pomposity.The marble floors and finely crafted woodwork reflect the materials of theother parts of the building, but there is an atmosphere in the place. It feelsas if the opulent surroundings beckon the student to work towards the daywhen they might walks these hallways as a barrister. There are glass paneddoors on either side of the hall, and a solid wood door at the north end.

The hall is built from all of the materials made to assemble the rest of thebuilding, except for the doors which are paned with glass. All of them exceptfor the solid door at the halls end. Each of the windowed doors is one of theentrances to a classroom. As you visit the rooms, gain the knowledge you willneed to pass the exam. The solid door at the end of the hall is the exam room.The Members of the Judicatory Board of Exodus wish you the best in your study.

In sharp contrast to he other parts of the lavish building, this room isstark, and all business. It is windowless, but well lit. It has furnishings,but nothing that looks comfortable. Once you feel you are ready for the examthat will allow you to practice law, contact an immortal on the judiciaryboard to administer your test. Be prepared by purchasing your exam bookletand pencil at the reception area. Good Luck!

The room is filled with the common furnishings of a place of teaching. Thereis a large desk at the front of the room, and smaller desks and chairs fillmost of the remainder of the space. The odd feature of the rooms in the LawSchool is the lack of windows. The staff of the college must be trying toavoid all outside interference in the learning process. After all, the fineinstruction received here is not cheap.

The room is filled with the common furnishings of a place of teaching. Thereis a large desk at the front of the room, and smaller desks and chairs fillmost of the remainder of the space. An old cobbled pathway has been built between the Gallows Square and theCourts Building. It isn't very wide, but it would seem that, if needed, threemen could walk abreast. It might make you wonder just how many people havebeen dragged from the building out to the square with a guard on each arm.The building is quite a bit longer north and south than east and west, andrises three stories. It is made from quarried stone, and is windowed on thefirst and third floors.

`oThis room has none of the fine wood finish of the rest of the building. Itis the same hewn stone that makes up the exterior face of the building. Theonly furnishings are long benches which line the west and north walls, and atable and chairs in the center of the room. These affects are all made ofmetal, which is not in keeping with the decor, but in this circumstance itis quite understandable. If you find yourself being held here, the chancesare that your on your way to court...be on your best behavior.

Rooms.MaxMsg: The pipe ahead is occupied.
Rooms.RoomDescription: Glub! Oh no...the end of the pipe is submurged! Well, there is no turningback at this point. You best grab the biggest lungfull of foul air that youcan manage, and push your way out. At this point, you wonder whether theescapees before you made it to safety, or whether your bones will become apart of a long testament to the futile efforts of escape from the gaol.

Rooms.MaxMsg: The tunnel is too small for another person.
Rooms.RoomDescription: Looks like someone has been busy! There are hand dug tunnels under thefloor of one of the cells. It doesn't seem that there has been any workdone recently, and it may be that it's due to the lack of a cellmate. Oncedown in the tunnel, it is impossible to climb back up alone. It would takesome kind of rope or a strong hand to get back to the cell. The largertunnel runs to the north and south, and a side tunnel runs off to the west.

Rooms.MaxMsg: The tunnel is too small for another person.
Rooms.RoomDescription: the hastily built tunnel is surprisingly passable. You would think that thespeed in which the prisoners were working would lead to a cramped space,but it looks as if the loose dirt permitted some ease in digging. The soilhas fallen quite a bit from the roof of the adit, but it looks like it shouldhold for the time being. Waiting around in this passage, however, would notbe advised. The passage opens up and tees to the north.

The soilhas fallen quite a bit from the roof of the adit, but it looks like it shouldhold for the time being. Waiting around in this passage, however, would notbe advised.

Rooms.MaxMsg: The tunnel is too small for another person.
Rooms.RoomDescription: The western adit of the secretly built tunnel system is a little slick. Itlooks as if some water seeps through the walls and floor. Getting dirtyand covered with cobwebs is part of the other tunnel, and it looks as ifgetting muddy is part of this one. The tunnel slopes downward a bit, so youmay want to watch your step...

Splash!  Well, the slick mud turned to muddy water, and it's another deadend.  The creators of the tunnel system certainly ran into troubles.  Itlooks as if the excavation work had to end due to the proximity ofthe riverto the west of the gaol.  It must be that they hoped to find daylight at theedge of the river bank, but instead found the river.  You look to see ifthere is a shaft leading upward, but alas, there is none.  The fear of acave-in of the wet earth must have been too great.

Rooms.MaxMsg: The tunnel is too small for another person.
Rooms.RoomDescription: The passage built by the prisoners has punched through to what looks likean old utility tunnel. There are places on the walls where torches may havebeen lodges, and a few long forgotten tools rust on the floor. The wallshave been notched in a manner that allows for old clay piping to be lainwith the length of the passage. In many places the wall has fallen, coveringthe pipe with the reddish brown dirt, but it looks like the pipe is intact.By the fall of the pipe, it isn't difficult to imagine what this pipe did,or may still, carry to the river.

Rooms.MaxMsg: The tunnel is too small for another person.
Rooms.RoomDescription: The old utility tunnel runs roughly in an east and west direction. It lookslike no one has been here in quite some time. The place is covered with alltypes of cobwebs and the last people here left some cloth items that arerotted to almost nothing. The way to the east is blocked by a cave-in whichmay explain why there has been no activity. The large pipe that runs withthe passage seems intact as far as you can see. Although there is not a foulsmell in the air, it is certainly quite stale.

Rooms.MaxMsg: The tunnel is too small for another person.
Rooms.RoomDescription: The old utility tunnel runs roughly in an east and west direction. It lookslike no one has been here in quite some time. The place is covered with alltypes of cobwebs and the last people here left some cloth items that arerotted to almost nothing. The pipe that runs along the tunnel has been beenbroken by someone. It is the top that has been cracked and broken in, so noeffluent runs out. But, it is easy to tell by the smell, this is the pipethat carries waste away from the building. It looks large enough in diameterto fit you, and it looks like the only way out...

Rooms.MaxMsg: That pipe isn't big enough!
Rooms.RoomDescription: Phew! As you cram your way down the disgusting pipe you no longer wonderabout the cost of freedom. Right now, its about the cost of the lunch youare trying to hold down. The stench is horrific, but the worst part is notbeing able to see the end of the pipe. By the fall, you know your headingin the right direction...but if there is no way out, there is also no wayback.

Rooms.MaxMsg: That pipe isn't big enough!
Rooms.RoomDescription: Although the muck in the pipe makes sliding along easy, you wonder if thepipe contains enough air for you to make it to the end. You forget just howfoul smelling the pipe has become, and gasp for the rancid air as if it werea fresh spring morning. You might be able to slip back a bit...but you wouldnever make it back out of the pipe. Your only hope is to press on towardwhat ominously sounds like rushing water.

Rooms.MaxMsg: The tunnel is too small for you to fit...
Rooms.RoomDescription: The south portion of the tunnel ends here, and it is easy to see the reason.It seems the tunnelers struck a large boulder which made this directionimpassable. There are marks around the edges of the stone made by the futileefforts to move the stone. There is only one option, return the same way asyou entered, just as the people before you must have done.
